               <msContents>
                  <summary>An unillustrated copy of the <title>Fatḥ′nāmah-ʼi Ṣāḥibqirānī</title>
                     (Book of Conquest by the Lord of the Conjunction), composed by historian
                        <persName key="person_95224252" role="aut"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/95224252/">Sharaf al-Dīn ʻAlī Yazdī (d.
                        1454)</persName> as an abridgement that omits passages of poetry from his
                     longer work, <title>Ẓafarnāmah</title> (Book of Victory). He completed both
                     works on behalf of the Timurid prince and bibliophile, <persName
                        role="pat subject dte" key="person_f1545">Ibrāhīm Sulṭān b. Shāh Rukh
                        (1394–1435)</persName> in order to chronicle the life and exploits of his
                     patron's grandfather, Central Asian ruler <persName role="subject"
                        key="person_63984707" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/63984707">Tīmūr (b. 1336, r.
                        1370–1405)</persName>, founder of the Timurid dynasty (1370–1507), and his
                     son and successor <persName role="subject" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/24010955"
                        key="person_24010955">Shāh Rukh Mīrzā (b. 1337, r. 1405–1447)</persName>.
                     The author derived the first part of his work from an earlier history completed
                     by Baghdad resident <persName role="ant" key="person_191145542438696641182"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/191145542438696641182">Niẓām al-Dīn Shāmī (fl. ca.
                        1392–1402)</persName> in an ornate style at Timur's request in 1402. A
                     scribe named <persName role="scr" xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc">‘Abd Allāh b.
                        Ādam</persName> completed this volume on <date calendar="#Hrijri-qamari"
                        when="1501-05-25">26 Shavvāl 906 AH (15 May 1501 [Julian/25 May 1501
                        CE])</date>, hence the earliest of nine copies of this work held in the
                     Rylands.</summary>

